<br>
It was more from the Arab side.. I was with Arab friends, we went as a small group (three of us), travelled through the Sinai to get in.  At the border, the security folks asked where we were planning to go in Israel, and completely naive I said &quot;West Jerusalem&quot;.. well, it was time for me to pull up a chair because I sat at the border for, and I'm not exaggerating, five hours.  They went through every iota of every thing I was carrying.. checked all the seams in every article of clothing, got out little chemistry kits to check any substances in my &quot;toilet&quot;, took me in a back room and searched through my hair, it went on and on.. all the time they have the largish guys standing around with the x-ray glasses (of course, not the nerdy ones you see in older movies, the cool ones that look almost like Ray-bans, lol <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ).. that said, they were curtly polite, no one was rude, it was like they were just doing their job.<br>
<br>
Inside Israel I was more interested in historical sites, Christian, Jewish and Muslim.  I had to lie to get into the mosque compound (I wasn't &quot;officially&quot; Muslim yet), as they were only allowing Muslims inside.. which thinking back is interesting, because it meant, at least how I look at it, they were trying to keep the peace and prevent clashes... I don't know if they'd had people try to get in there and cause trouble or what.  So I basically did the whole &quot;traditional&quot; tour - Via Dolorosa, Mount of Olives, Wailing Wall, Gate of David, Bethlehem, etc. etc... we did go through Eilat, which I didn't like so much (a typical beach resort), and visited some of the newer parts of Jerusalem, but my interest wasn't there.. I like the old parts <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
We did a small amount of driving around (bus and taxi), so saw the Dead Sea, bought some salty mud facial stuff to bring home, that sort of thing.<br>
<br>
What I did notice was an overall atmosphere of tension.  I didn't see any scuffles myself, but there was just this feeling, I don't know how to describe it, a vibe or something.  I'm sure it must be worse now.  There was a quietness, although obviously there were the noises of day-to-day living, I'm not sure I'm describing it right.  It reminded me, in a way, of when I visited communist Hungary.  There too was a sort of oppressive atmosphere.  You didn't see people walking around laughing, joking.. the joys of life were not evident.. <br>
<br>
I guess overall my comment would be that it's a nice place to visit, but I wouldn't want to live there.  I think that's something we as Americans really have only just begun to feel.  I mean, people used to tell me they could tell I was American just by the way I would walk.. you know, we tend to have a kind of bouncy, excited, alive, urgent way we walk around.. I can see it now that someone has pointed it out to me.. and you can see that it's different from other people.. I don't know, maybe I'm totally flaking out, but I feel that since it's been so long since we've lived under any kind of oppression, whether overt or covert, we still have that kind of optimism, and it reflects in our society and even in the way we are.<br>
<br>
